Second Lady Karen Pence, accompanied by Acting Deputy Secretary of Veterans Affairs Pamela Powers, visited Charleston to learn about veteran suicide prevention efforts. They toured the Mental Health Research Building at the Ralph H. Johnson Veterans Affairs Medical Center, where they viewed artwork created by a veteran in the Hall of Heroes exhibit. They also witnessed a demonstration of Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation, which is used to treat veterans suffering from depression and other psychological health conditions that can lead to suicide. Additionally, they observed a virtual PTSD treatment with physiological monitoring. Following the tour, Pence participated in a roundtable discussion with researchers and VA officials. She highlighted her role with PREVENTS, a three-year effort launched by President Trump to empower veterans and prevent suicide.